And for the purposes of the demo,

00:01:02.959 --> 00:01:04.959
it's going to shut down the session.

00:01:04.959 --> 00:01:06.959
That will come in later.

00:01:06.959 --> 00:01:08.959
But nothing surprising.

00:01:08.959 --> 00:01:12.959
I mean, if we want, we can kind of sneak what the tool output was.

00:01:12.959 --> 00:01:16.959
But we can see that it asked the available tool call to ask about Chicago.

00:01:16.959 --> 00:01:20.959
And then wrote up a summary of that information.

00:01:21.279 --> 00:01:23.279
Nothing too fancy.

00:01:23.279 --> 00:01:27.279
But let's actually look what happens underneath the hood.

00:01:27.279 --> 00:01:29.279
So we'll rerun that.

00:01:29.279 --> 00:01:31.279
And we'll say,

00:01:31.279 --> 00:01:33.279
What is the weather in Chicago?

00:01:39.279 --> 00:01:41.279
Tool call.

00:01:41.279 --> 00:01:43.279
Responding.

00:01:43.279 --> 00:01:45.279
And then we're done.

00:01:45.279 --> 00:01:47.279
After a few seconds.

00:01:47.279 --> 00:01:49.279
Awesome.

00:01:49.599 --> 00:01:53.599
Let's check out the chart on the left.

00:01:53.599 --> 00:01:55.599
So we have

00:01:55.599 --> 00:01:59.599
a simple session start.

00:01:59.599 --> 00:02:01.599
And then we have some reactive updating.

00:02:01.599 --> 00:02:05.599
And this is like the whole crux of the talk today.

00:02:05.599 --> 00:02:07.599
In that this little reactive update

00:02:07.599 --> 00:02:09.600
is going to spawn Claude

00:02:09.600 --> 00:02:11.600
to do some communication.

00:02:11.600 --> 00:02:13.600
That is going to make a post request.

00:02:13.600 --> 00:02:15.600
And then it's going to stream back some results

00:02:15.600 --> 00:02:17.600
if they're there.

00:02:17.919 --> 00:02:19.919
This then prompted to have us

00:02:19.919 --> 00:02:21.919
go into executing a tool call.

00:02:21.919 --> 00:02:23.919
Which I just happened to do through Mirai.

00:02:23.919 --> 00:02:25.919
To go through a background R process.

00:02:25.919 --> 00:02:27.919
That itself said,

00:02:27.919 --> 00:02:29.919
Hey, I'm going to go get the weather forecast.

00:02:29.919 --> 00:02:31.919
And it happened to do

00:02:31.919 --> 00:02:33.919
a hit or two requests.

00:02:33.919 --> 00:02:35.919
And then finally,

00:02:35.919 --> 00:02:37.919
I came back with Claude

00:02:37.919 --> 00:02:39.919
and

00:02:39.919 --> 00:02:41.919
with the post to say here's the response.

00:02:41.919 --> 00:02:43.919
And then we're streaming back

00:02:43.919 --> 00:02:45.919
results as Claude does within the website.

00:02:46.240 --> 00:02:48.240
This is awesome.

00:02:48.240 --> 00:02:50.240
I now have an 8 second demo

00:02:50.240 --> 00:02:52.240
and I can point fingers

00:02:52.240 --> 00:02:54.240
as to who took the most time.

00:02:54.240 --> 00:02:56.240
In this case,

00:02:56.240 --> 00:02:58.240
while it is about 7 seconds here,

00:02:58.240 --> 00:03:00.240
3 seconds was first Claude.

00:03:00.240 --> 00:03:02.240
Then the tool

00:03:02.240 --> 00:03:04.240
was here

00:03:04.240 --> 00:03:06.240
and it took about 650 milliseconds.

00:03:06.240 --> 00:03:08.240
Half a second roughly.

00:03:08.240 --> 00:03:10.240
And then finally Claude's response

00:03:10.240 --> 00:03:12.240
took another roughly 3 seconds.

00:03:12.240 --> 00:03:14.240
So my tool call

00:03:14.559 --> 00:03:16.559
is of the big picture,

00:03:16.559 --> 00:03:18.559
not the big time sync.

00:03:18.559 --> 00:03:20.559
But there are little locations

00:03:20.559 --> 00:03:22.559
where we can improve what's happening.

00:03:26.559 --> 00:03:28.559
This is all being done through OpenTelemetry.

00:03:28.559 --> 00:03:30.559
And OpenTelemetry,

00:03:30.559 --> 00:03:32.559
according to their website,

00:03:32.559 --> 00:03:34.559
is highly high quality,

00:03:34.559 --> 00:03:36.559
ubiquitous and portable telemetry

00:03:36.559 --> 00:03:38.559
to enable effective observability.

00:03:38.559 --> 00:03:40.559
If we're just looking at our app

00:03:40.559 --> 00:03:42.559
the way we were the first time,

00:03:42.880 --> 00:03:44.880
we can see what's happening on the surface

00:03:44.880 --> 00:03:46.880
but really what's happening underneath

00:03:46.880 --> 00:03:48.880
where the computations are being done,

00:03:48.880 --> 00:03:50.880
that's the important part to the developers

00:03:50.880 --> 00:03:52.880
and during production.

00:03:52.880 --> 00:03:54.880
OpenTelemetry provides a set

00:03:54.880 --> 00:03:56.880
of APIs and libraries and agents

00:03:56.880 --> 00:03:58.880
and instrumentation

00:03:58.880 --> 00:04:00.880
to provide observability

00:04:00.880 --> 00:04:02.880
for your applications.

00:04:02.880 --> 00:04:04.880
In this case,

00:04:04.880 --> 00:04:06.880
OpenTelemetry is being integrated

00:04:06.880 --> 00:04:08.880
into the R ecosystem

00:04:08.880 --> 00:04:10.880
and is currently under development.

00:04:11.199 --> 00:04:13.199
So let's look at this a little bit more generically.

00:04:13.199 --> 00:04:15.199
OpenTelemetry is really good

00:04:15.199 --> 00:04:17.200
at a burst of an action

00:04:17.200 --> 00:04:19.200
such as a user clicked

00:04:19.200 --> 00:04:21.200
the website or Shiny's

00:04:21.200 --> 00:04:23.200
reactivity just started.

00:04:23.200 --> 00:04:25.200
After this action

00:04:25.200 --> 00:04:27.200
you'll have different services

00:04:27.200 --> 00:04:29.200
be engaged,

00:04:29.200 --> 00:04:31.200
in this case the green, then the blue,

00:04:31.200 --> 00:04:33.200
then the yellow, which then calls a database

00:04:33.200 --> 00:04:35.200
and then they undo

00:04:35.200 --> 00:04:37.200
their work since they're done processing.

00:04:37.200 --> 00:04:39.200
So we can see how long the blue,

00:04:39.519 --> 00:04:41.519
then how long

00:04:41.519 --> 00:04:43.519
the yellow take,

00:04:43.519 --> 00:04:45.519
and then finally accessing that database

00:04:45.519 --> 00:04:47.519
how long of your computation time

00:04:47.519 --> 00:04:49.519
is performing that.

00:04:53.519 --> 00:04:55.519
So, seems like a good idea

00:04:55.519 --> 00:04:57.519
to have for production.

00:04:57.519 --> 00:04:59.519
How can we do it? What does it take to integrate?

00:04:59.519 --> 00:05:01.519
There's two steps.

00:05:01.519 --> 00:05:03.519
First one is we need to install OTEL

00:05:03.519 --> 00:05:05.519
and OTEL SDK.

00:05:05.519 --> 00:05:07.519
Packages will do the OTEL for you.

00:05:07.839 --> 00:05:09.839
You as an app author

00:05:09.839 --> 00:05:11.839
will need OTEL SDK

00:05:11.839 --> 00:05:13.839
and I'd like to take a small

00:05:13.839 --> 00:05:15.839
pause here to thank Gabor

00:05:15.839 --> 00:05:17.839
because this went from concept

00:05:17.839 --> 00:05:19.839
to implementation and on CRAN

00:05:19.839 --> 00:05:21.839
in a really fast time and there's lots

00:05:21.839 --> 00:05:23.839
of iterations so I just have

00:05:23.839 --> 00:05:25.839
to give a big shout out to Gabor.

00:05:28.839 --> 00:05:30.839
The second thing you need to do is to

00:05:30.839 --> 00:05:32.839
add three, roughly three

00:05:32.839 --> 00:05:34.839
environment variables. It depends on your endpoint.

00:05:34.839 --> 00:05:36.839
In the demo

00:05:37.160 --> 00:05:39.160
I happen to be using LogFire.

00:05:39.160 --> 00:05:41.160
It's a third party website

00:05:41.160 --> 00:05:43.160
that can host the OpenTelemetry data

00:05:43.160 --> 00:05:45.160
and the environment variables

00:05:45.160 --> 00:05:47.160
what they are doing

00:05:47.160 --> 00:05:49.160
is they're saying please send the information

00:05:49.160 --> 00:05:51.160
according to HTTP protocol

00:05:51.160 --> 00:05:53.160
and then the location

00:05:53.160 --> 00:05:55.160
that you're going to is my LogFire website

00:05:55.160 --> 00:05:57.160
and then I'm adding in some authorization.

00:05:59.160 --> 00:06:01.160
There's a nice, nice

00:06:01.160 --> 00:06:03.160
article that I tested out

00:06:03.160 --> 00:06:05.160
different locations just to give you

00:06:05.480 --> 00:06:07.480
different interfaces for the demo today

00:06:07.480 --> 00:06:09.480
but it's there in the OTEL SDK

00:06:09.480 --> 00:06:11.480
Collecting Telemetry Data

00:06:11.480 --> 00:06:13.480
article.

00:06:15.480 --> 00:06:17.480
So you're probably seeing these

00:06:17.480 --> 00:06:19.480
flame graph looking things and you're like

00:06:19.480 --> 00:06:21.480
well, what about

00:06:21.480 --> 00:06:23.480
Profvis? What about ReactLog?

00:06:23.480 --> 00:06:25.480
This is how I debug my applications already.

00:06:25.480 --> 00:06:27.480
And Profvis

00:06:27.480 --> 00:06:29.480
it allows for local

00:06:29.480 --> 00:06:31.480
R code profiling

00:06:31.480 --> 00:06:33.480
and it also displays some

00:06:33.480 --> 00:06:35.480
memory usage as well.

00:06:35.480 --> 00:06:37.480
In ReactLog you can

00:06:37.480 --> 00:06:39.480
replay all of the local

00:06:39.480 --> 00:06:41.480
reactivity that you have captured

00:06:41.480 --> 00:06:43.480
and it always displays a full dependency

00:06:43.480 --> 00:06:45.480
graph for every reactive component

00:06:45.480 --> 00:06:47.480
within your application.

00:06:47.480 --> 00:06:49.480
So if you have a very large application

00:06:49.480 --> 00:06:51.480
you'll have a very large connected graph.

00:06:51.480 --> 00:06:53.480
I highly recommend it if things aren't working

00:06:53.480 --> 00:06:55.480
the way you expect it.

00:06:57.480 --> 00:06:59.480
The bad part about both of these packages

00:06:59.480 --> 00:07:01.480
is that they only support the main R process.

00:07:01.480 --> 00:07:03.480
So if you're using

00:07:03.480 --> 00:07:05.480
Mirai which does computing

00:07:05.480 --> 00:07:07.480
on a different R process

00:07:07.480 --> 00:07:09.480
we don't have access

00:07:09.480 --> 00:07:11.480
to that with Profvis or ReactLog.

00:07:11.480 --> 00:07:13.480
But with OpenTelemetry

00:07:13.480 --> 00:07:15.480
we can pass through some extra headers

00:07:15.480 --> 00:07:17.480
and Mirai can do the proper

00:07:17.480 --> 00:07:19.480
reporting.

00:07:19.480 --> 00:07:21.480
Also Profvis

00:07:21.480 --> 00:07:23.480
and ReactLog

00:07:23.480 --> 00:07:25.480
are not for production.

00:07:25.480 --> 00:07:27.480
By definition both of those packages

00:07:27.480 --> 00:07:29.480
produce a memory leak.

00:07:29.480 --> 00:07:31.480
They're constantly recording.

00:07:31.480 --> 00:07:33.480
Even if we were to write out to disk

00:07:33.480 --> 00:07:35.480
you're going to run out of space eventually.

00:07:35.480 --> 00:07:37.480
So both of these packages

00:07:37.480 --> 00:07:39.480
are great for local development,

00:07:39.480 --> 00:07:41.480
great for debugging, but I do not

00:07:41.480 --> 00:07:43.480
recommend them for production.

00:07:47.480 --> 00:07:49.480
So let's look at these flame graphs.

00:07:49.480 --> 00:07:51.480
In this case

00:07:51.480 --> 00:07:53.480
we have a long grey one,

00:07:53.480 --> 00:07:55.480
a green, blue and gold

00:07:55.480 --> 00:07:57.480
and how can we improve

00:07:57.480 --> 00:07:59.480
those performances?

00:07:59.480 --> 00:08:01.480
There's two approaches that we can do.

00:08:01.480 --> 00:08:03.480
The first one we want to reduce the length

00:08:03.480 --> 00:08:05.480
of the long running spans.

00:08:05.480 --> 00:08:07.480
In this picture and in the demos

00:08:07.480 --> 00:08:09.480
there wasn't something that was like

00:08:09.480 --> 00:08:11.480
oh I ran for 10 seconds

00:08:11.480 --> 00:08:13.480
when I really want it to be one second long.

00:08:13.480 --> 00:08:15.480
That would be a situation that you want

00:08:15.480 --> 00:08:17.480
to reduce it, but now you can point fingers

00:08:17.480 --> 00:08:19.480
as to who is the culprit.

00:08:19.480 --> 00:08:21.480
And then the other one is

00:08:21.480 --> 00:08:23.480
to limit excessive span nesting.

00:08:23.480 --> 00:08:25.480
In this demo it's like

00:08:25.480 --> 00:08:27.480
five nesting layers.

00:08:27.480 --> 00:08:29.480
Not an issue.

00:08:29.480 --> 00:08:31.480
I'd say 10, not an issue.

00:08:31.480 --> 00:08:33.479
When you're expecting 10

00:08:33.479 --> 00:08:35.479
and it's 100, probably an issue.

00:08:37.479 --> 00:08:39.479
But it's excessive span nesting.

00:08:39.479 --> 00:08:41.479
Similar to Profiz,

00:08:41.479 --> 00:08:43.479
the graph has to go up and down

00:08:43.479 --> 00:08:45.479
naturally, but if all of a sudden

00:08:45.479 --> 00:08:47.479
you see everyone's like

00:08:47.479 --> 00:08:49.479
mid mountains and then you have a

00:08:49.479 --> 00:08:51.479
giant spike out of nowhere,

00:08:51.479 --> 00:08:53.479
something to investigate. Maybe we can reduce

00:08:53.479 --> 00:08:55.479
the overhead.

