We can, one, move work

00:11:45.479 --> 00:11:47.479
outside of Shiny. This is pretty often.

00:11:47.479 --> 00:11:49.479
In the

00:11:49.479 --> 00:11:51.479
standard case, if you

00:11:51.479 --> 00:11:53.479
have consistent computing being done,

00:11:53.479 --> 00:11:55.479
maybe lift it outside into

00:11:55.479 --> 00:11:57.479
your global.R or

00:11:57.479 --> 00:11:59.479
try to do some preprocessing and have

00:11:59.479 --> 00:12:01.479
that be loaded before your server function.

00:12:01.479 --> 00:12:03.479
Just relocating it

00:12:03.479 --> 00:12:05.479
sometimes makes a big, big

00:12:05.479 --> 00:12:07.479
difference.

00:12:07.479 --> 00:12:09.479
Two, make your code faster.

00:12:09.479 --> 00:12:11.479
If you can't move it outside the function,

00:12:11.479 --> 00:12:13.479
instead maybe use

00:12:13.479 --> 00:12:15.479
DuckDB as a backend. Even if it's

00:12:15.479 --> 00:12:17.479
still being processed in memory, it'll

00:12:17.479 --> 00:12:19.479
possibly be faster than

00:12:19.479 --> 00:12:21.479
what you have already

00:12:21.479 --> 00:12:23.479
with dplyr.

00:12:23.479 --> 00:12:25.479
Use caching.

00:12:25.479 --> 00:12:27.479
If it applies, if you're returning

00:12:27.479 --> 00:12:29.479
the same answer for the same input,

00:12:29.479 --> 00:12:31.479
maybe we can add a layer of caching on top of

00:12:31.479 --> 00:12:33.479
that and then your spans will just

00:12:33.479 --> 00:12:35.479
disappear.

00:12:35.479 --> 00:12:37.479
And then finally,

00:12:37.479 --> 00:12:39.479
use some non-blocking reactivity.

00:12:39.479 --> 00:12:41.479
In the demo, I happened

00:12:41.479 --> 00:12:43.479
to have the tool call use Mirai

00:12:43.479 --> 00:12:45.479
to pull it off the main

00:12:45.479 --> 00:12:47.479
R process so that others could do work.

00:12:47.479 --> 00:12:49.479
I wasn't showing it in the use case,

00:12:49.479 --> 00:12:51.479
but it did pull it off

00:12:51.479 --> 00:12:53.479
the main R process, and then that way it wasn't

00:12:53.479 --> 00:12:55.479
blocking others to stream

00:12:55.479 --> 00:12:57.479
or to do any calculations.

00:13:01.479 --> 00:13:03.479
And then repeat.

00:13:03.479 --> 00:13:05.479
When you do make some

00:13:05.479 --> 00:13:07.479
of these changes, you may have to go back

00:13:07.479 --> 00:13:09.479
up to number two and see

00:13:09.479 --> 00:13:11.479
profvis and reevaluate your

00:13:11.479 --> 00:13:13.479
app, because sometimes just by enabling

00:13:13.479 --> 00:13:15.479
caching, spans

00:13:15.479 --> 00:13:17.479
will just disappear and your

00:13:17.479 --> 00:13:19.479
computation will be very

00:13:19.479 --> 00:13:21.479
different in shape compared

00:13:21.479 --> 00:13:23.479
to the first time.

00:13:26.479 --> 00:13:28.479
And some next steps.

00:13:28.479 --> 00:13:30.479
This is all in active development.

