slower than that, so

00:15:44.479 --> 00:15:46.479
I think we're okay.

00:15:46.479 --> 00:15:48.479
How is OpenTelemetry

00:15:48.479 --> 00:15:50.479
different from writing my own logs?

00:15:50.479 --> 00:15:52.479
Is it just another logging framework?

00:15:52.479 --> 00:15:54.479
It is just

00:15:54.479 --> 00:15:56.479
a logging framework, absolutely it is.

00:15:56.479 --> 00:15:58.479
It should be treated just like that.

00:15:58.479 --> 00:16:00.479
You should have log,

00:16:00.479 --> 00:16:02.479
debug, trace, fatal, error,

00:16:02.479 --> 00:16:04.479
all the different things, just like a

00:16:04.479 --> 00:16:06.479
logging framework. I think the interesting

00:16:06.479 --> 00:16:08.479
part here is that

00:16:08.479 --> 00:16:10.479
Otel is defined to have a

00:16:10.479 --> 00:16:12.479
collector, and so you can have

00:16:12.479 --> 00:16:14.479
multiple Shiny applications. They can all be

00:16:14.479 --> 00:16:16.479
pointing to the same collector.

00:16:16.479 --> 00:16:18.479
The collector will get a batch and then

00:16:18.479 --> 00:16:20.479
send upstream to the third-party

00:16:20.479 --> 00:16:22.479
website, and that

00:16:22.479 --> 00:16:24.479
process is much better than

00:16:24.479 --> 00:16:26.479
logs. Logs are wonderful if you

00:16:26.479 --> 00:16:28.479
want to send, you own the

00:16:28.479 --> 00:16:30.479
server, you only have one server,

00:16:30.479 --> 00:16:32.479
and you're writing to a single location,

00:16:32.479 --> 00:16:34.479
sure, just use logs, but

00:16:34.479 --> 00:16:36.479
when you start having multiple

00:16:36.479 --> 00:16:38.479
machines that may or may not exist in five

00:16:38.479 --> 00:16:40.479
minutes, like having OpenTelemetry

00:16:40.479 --> 00:16:42.479
collect to a third-party

00:16:42.479 --> 00:16:44.479
site, it makes it

00:16:44.479 --> 00:16:46.479
that much easier.

